{{short description|Theory of continuous nonconformist Christian Church}} '''Baptist successionism''' (or '''Baptist perpetuity''') is one of several theories on the [[Baptists#Origins|origin and continuation of Baptist churches]]. The theory postulates an unbroken lineage of churches (since the days of [[John the Baptist]], who baptized [[Jesus in Christianity|Christ]]) which have held beliefs similar to those of current [[Baptists]]. Groups often included in this lineage include the [[Montanists]], [[Paulicianism|Paulicians]], [[Cathari]], [[Waldenses]], [[Albigenses]], and [[Anabaptist]]s.{{sfn|Patterson|1969|p= 9}}
== Articulation of the theory ==
[[File:The Trail of Blood.jpg|thumb|upright=1.75|Diagram representing ''[[The Trail of Blood]]'' as presented by [[James Milton Carroll]]]] The perpetuity view is often identified with ''[[The Trail of Blood]]'', a pamphlet by [[James Milton Carroll]] published in 1931.{{sfn|McBeth|1987|pp=59–60}} Other Baptist writers who held the perpetuity view are [[John T. Christian]], [[Thomas Crosby (Baptist)|Thomas Crosby]], G. H. Orchard, J. M. Cramp, William Cathcart, Adam Taylor and D. B. Ray.{{sfnm |1a1=McBeth |1y=1987 |1pp=59–60 |2a1=Torbet |2y=1975 |2p=18}}
This view was once commonly held among Baptists.{{sfn|Torbet|1975|p=18}} Since the end of the 19th century, however, the theory has increasingly come under attack and today has been largely discredited.{{sfnm |1a1=Brackney |1y=2004 |2a1=McGoldrick |2y=2000}}{{page needed|date=February 2013}} Nonetheless, the view continued to be the prevailing view among Baptists of the [[Southern United States]] into the latter 20th century.{{sfn|Patterson|1969|p=6}} It is now identified primarily with [[Landmarkism]], though not exclusively so.{{sfnm |1a1=McBeth |1y=1987 |1p=58 |2a1=Patterson |2y=1969 |2p=6}} The concept finds its parallels in the [[Roman Catholic]], [[Eastern Orthodox]], and [[Anglican]] doctrine of [[apostolic succession]] and stands in contrast to the restorationist views of [[Mormons|Latter Day Saints]] and the [[Stone-Campbell Restoration Movement]].{{sfn|Torbet|1975|p=19}}
== Modern rejection of the theory ==
Since the end of the 19th century the trend in academic Baptist [[historiography]] has been away from the successionist viewpoint to the view that modern day Baptists are an outgrowth of 17th-century [[English Separatist|English Separatism]].{{sfn|Cross|1990|p=174}} This shift precipitated a controversy among [[Southern Baptists]] which occasioned the [[Southern Baptist Convention#Whitsitt controversy|forced resignation of William H. Whitsitt]], a professor at [[Southern Baptist Seminary]], in 1898 from the seminary for advocating the new view, though his views continued to be taught in the seminary after his departure.{{sfn|McBeth|1987|pp=457–458}}
== See also == *[[Landmarkism]] *[[Restorationism]] *{{section link|Christadelphians#Other historical groups and individuals with some shared doctrines}} *{{section link|Gospel Hall Assemblies#History}} *''The Pilgrim Church'' by [[Edmund Hamer Broadbent]]
